Microorganisms. A large number of pharmaceuticals originate from microorganisms; they range from whole microorganisms, e.g., spores of Lactobacillus sporogenes, through biomass used as food/feed supplements, e.g., single cell proteins, to a variety for highly valuable compounds like antibiotics, vitamins, enzymes, organic acids, etc.Plant cell cultures. Some biochemicals of pharmaceutical value are produced by cultured plant cells, e.g., shikonin, berberine, ginseng biomass, and Taxol. Taxol is produced from cell cultures of Taxus spp. grown in 75,000 I bioreactors and is used for the treatment of breast and ovarian cancers.Animal cell cultures. Cultured animal cells are the source of several compounds used in the treatment of diseases, e.g., angiogenic factor, interleukin-2. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
